Media coverage of climate change has often emphasized catastrophic scenarios and extreme weather attribution, contributing to heightened public alarm. New features like App Builder and Workflows allow employees to create custom applications and automate tasks using only conversational prompts. This move represents Microsoft's most significant effort to integrate AI into software development for non-developers. Users can describe an application, such as a project tracker, and Copilot will generate a functional app with a database and user interface. The Workflows agent automates routine tasks across Microsoft products, while a simplified agent-building platform allows for specialized AI assistants. These new capabilities are included at no extra cost to the existing Microsoft 365 Copilot subscription. This expansion is the culmination of Microsoft's nine-year focus on democratizing software development through its Power Platform. The integration into Copilot brings these low-code/no-code tools directly into the familiar AI conversational interface. Professional developers are still recommended for systems interacting with external parties due to increased risk. Microsoft also provides governance controls for IT administrators to manage employee-created applications. The company aims to empower a vast number of workers to become software builders, fundamentally changing the nature of office work. These features build upon Microsoft's deep partnership with OpenAI and its strategy of embedding AI across its product portfolio.

PSA: I had a lot of issues with #Thunderbird being unbearably slow and eating up insane amounts of memory.

Turns out the user profile I had been using has been hanging around since 2012 (!), so this had accumulated 14 years of cruft, despite the occasional folder cleaning.

Created a new profile and moved all my settings over, which was annoying, but definitely worth having a usable email client again 👍
